Board representation: rank8 to rank1 presumably.

Given the board ASCII:

Rank8: ♜ ♞ ♝ ♛ ♚ ♝ ♞ ♜  => black pieces on back rank.
Rank7: ♟ ♟ ♟ ⭘ ♟ ♟ ♟ ♟ => black pawns on a7,b7,c7, e7,f7,g7,h7; d7 empty.
Rank6: ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ => empty.
Rank5: ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ => black pawn on d5.
Rank4: ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ => empty.
Rank3: ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♙ ⭘ ⭘ ♙ ⭘ => white pawn on d3, white pawn on g3.
Rank2: ♙ ♙ ♙ ⭘ ♙ ♙ ⭘ ♙ => white pawns a2,b2,c2,e2,f2,h2; d2 empty, g2 empty.
Rank1: ♖ ♘ ♗ ♕ ♔ ♗ ♘ ♖ => white pieces standard.

It's black's turn. Need legal moves for black. Let's compute. Black pieces: King e8, queen d8, rooks a8 h8, bishops c8 f8, knights b8 g8, pawns: a7,b7,c7, d5, e7,f7,g7,h7.

White pieces: king e1, queen d1, rooks a1 h1, bishops c1 f1, knights b1 g1, pawns: a2,b2,c2,d3,e2,f2,g3,h2.

We need to consider checks? Is black in check? White pieces attack e8? Let's see: White queen on d1 along diagonal to e2 f3 g4 h5 - not e8. Straight file d1 to d8: squares d2 empty, d3 white pawn blocks. So queen not delivering. Bishop c1 diagonal to d2 empty, e3 empty, f4 empty, g5 empty, h6 empty; not e8. Bishop f1 diagonal to e2 white pawn, blocked. Knights? b1 attacks a3, c3, d2, d0 (offboard), a... not e8. g1 attacks e2 (occupied white pawn), f3 empty, h3 empty, e0 offboard etc. Rooks not. Pawn attacks: white pawn on d3 attacks c4 and e4 (empty). Pawn g3 attacks f4 and h4. So black not in check.

Now compute possible moves. Typical opening moves. Let's list plausible good moves: Since black's pawn on d5 advanced, maybe capture on d3? Pawn on d5 can move to d4 (one step forward) if empty; d4 is empty. Could also capture c4 or e4, but none pieces. Could also capture en passant? White pawn on e2 hasn't moved two steps last move? unknown.

Other moves: develop knights: Nf6 (g8 to f6) is legal if f6 empty; yes. Ng8-e7? e7 occupied by pawn. Ng8-h6? h6 empty, but typical is Nf6.

Knight b8 to c6 (c6 empty), a6 empty.

Bishop c8 to g4? Path: d7 empty, e6 empty, f5 empty, g4 empty. So Bc8-g4 is possible, delivering pin maybe. Bishop c8 to b7? b7 occupied by pawn. To a6 empty diagonal? c8-b7 occupied, so no. Bishop f8 to e7 (occupied by pawn), g7 occupied by pawn, h6 empty? Path f8-g7 blocked by pawn, so bishop can't move.

Pawn moves: a7-a6 or a5 (two squares a7 to a5 if empty a6 empty). Both squares a6 empty, a5 empty? a5 empty (rank5 file a). So a7-a5 is possible if not blocked. b7-b5 possible (b6 empty, b5 empty). c7-c5 possible (c6 empty, c5 empty). e7-e5 possible (e6 empty, e5 empty). f7-f5 (f6 empty, f5 empty). g7-g5 (g6 empty, g5 empty). h7-h5 (h6 empty, h5 empty). Also pawn d5 can move to d4.

Capture possibilities: pawn on d5 could capture c4 (empty) or e4 (empty). Knight maybe capture something: Knight b8 can capture a6 (empty) c6 (empty) d7 (empty) d9 offboard a... none. Knight g8 can capture e7 (occupied) f6 empty, h6 empty, e9 offboard, f10 offboard, h10 offboard.

Bishop g4 would pin knight? Not.

We need to output a move in UCI format. Choose a solid developing move: Nf6 (g8f6). Let's verify square f6 empty. Yes.

So make_move g8f6.make_move g8f6
